"Yes, Captain. They should be on their way by now, they were still at the canteen to collect their rations."
"We will be relocated to the advanced operational base I-131, fifty miles outside Ianlos. Our task is to support the ongoing siege and the subsequent attack on Ianlos in order to drive out the rebels. There, we will establish a base camp at the foot of the mountains," explained Shaw. "Depart to your squads and mount up."
The company broke down into its respective squads, and the soldiers were distributed among the tanks by the sergeants.
"Hey Cohren, is Snowball still with Harris?"
"Do you mean the rooster that he stole?"
Cohren glanced over at one of the other tanks and spotted Harris with his squad. From the corner of his eye, he could make out the movement of a small rooster, scanning its surroundings with constant head turns.
"Yes, he's still with him," replied Cohren, as the hatch of the tank opened and the commander came into view.
"All tanks are moving out," the commander spoke slowly and calmly into his headset. The engines of the tank convoy and Strykers roared as they set in motion. The Kronos tank, which Cohren was riding on, jolted as the brakes were released and they fell into formation. The tanks moved in a wedge formation across the Itania Plain. Despite the winter storms freezing the marshlands and blanketing the woods in snow, mud was omnipresent.
"After about an hour, one of the recruits, whose name Cohren knew was Orson, began to speak. "Lieutenant, you've been here since the start of the war, right?"
"Yes, Operation Firestorm," replied Cohren. "We thought it would be wrapped up in a few weeks, but we underestimated it."
"Underestimated is a gross understatement," Nemic interjected into the conversation. "We weren't prepared for their arsenal and sheer number of troops. They destroyed the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks and the Erebus just last month. We should have seen them on our way."
"I stand firmly by the Federation's side," said Orson defiantly. "I won't let these terrorists intimidate me."
"But you say that now. But I've seen that most eighteen-year-old recruits like you take cover right away as soon as they hear a shot," Craith explained.
"We'll see about that," said Cohren laughing. Orson cut off the conversation.
"Exodus XO, Exodus CO," crackled Cohren's radio. "We're receiving heat signatures, approximately 300 meters out, 20 degrees right."
Cohren climbed up on the tank and put on his special glasses. As he switched them to "thermal" mode, he could make out the signatures in the distance.
"Yes, I see them," replied Cohren into his throat microphone.
"Are they hostile?" asked the other recruit, Natayla.
"Can't make them out," replied Cohren. He reached for his microphone and said, "Exodus Company, hold fire until under fire. Let's lure them out."
As they drew closer, the point-like thermal signatures began to take shape. As they got even closer, one of them hastily ran off to get something, only to return immediately to the small ridge where the others were positioned. The figures then lay down, assuming firing positions.
"We have hostile contact," Shaw yelled over the radio, as orange tracer rounds were fired from the ridge. As the tanks came under fire, the forward troops leapt down and took cover. A rocket whizzed past and slammed into the ground behind the formation, exploding and scattering debris and rubble onto one of the tanks. Another slammed sideways into a Stryker, an APS-Cerberus, and exploded. The crew scrambled out quickly and took cover as the ammunition erupted into the air.
"Iron 1-2 and 1-3, 25 degrees right, 300 meters. Fire at will," the commander of the tank convoy screamed over the radio.
"Send in the Sentis," Knoxx yelled out, observing the ridge with binoculars. The rear hatch of a Cerberus opened, and an unarmed soldier emerged, wearing a special headset. He barked orders into a square microphone, and two Sentis, officially known as Sentinels, burst out. Their thin, metallic arms and legs swinging forward, they sprinted into action, their weapons slung over their backs.
"Capture or kill?" asked Craith, as they watched.
"It appears to be a capture operation," Cohren speculated as the two Sentinels vanished into the ash and smoke cloud. Shouts and shots echoed from the ridge, but quickly fell silent. Shortly afterwards, the two Sentinels returned, dragging someone behind them, whose boots left tracks in the ground. After they returned to the safety of the convoy, they tossed the figure onto the ground. It groaned in pain as it landed hard in the mud and snow.
Shaw approached the figure, who was just trying to stand up. Then he turned to one of the Sentinels. "How many?"
"Three dead, Sir," the Sentinel replied. "The rest fled on foot."
Shaw nodded and turned to Cohren and Craith, who stood nearby. "Get rid of this guy for me!"
